reviewText: If you know TAXI but haven't taken the plunge then get this set! If you're considering it and are a fan of intelligently-written comedy acted by the best actors out there then you've come to the right place. Everyone here is top-shelf from the writer, actors and technical staff. These folks make it look easy, which good comedy is NOT. My favorite character is Reverend Jim. The writing for him is so wonderful and Christopher Lloyd is pitch-perfect in the part. His first full episode as a series regular is one of the funniest episodes EVER aired from ANY series.Be warned, some (most?) of the episodes have been edited (I suspect the masters used for these DVDs were the trimmed, syndication versions), but until we get them all complete & uncut on Blu-ray someday (pray for it, but don't hold your breath), this is what we've got to work with. Better than nothing. Audio & Video are OK, but nothing spectacular. Complete set has no special packaging; just the individual season boxes shrink-wrapped into one bundle. VERY lame. This series deserves much better treatment. But once again, it's all we've got until "someday" comes along.
summary: A great series. One of the all-time best, along with Barney Miller & M*A*S*H

reviewText: I got the complete series afew days ago , and stayed up all night watching it again.  About 4 am I realized just how much crap they the have on regular T.V.  today.  This is from the times of Night Court,  Really good cops shows like Barney  Miller  and Hill Street Blues.  Programs that you can get to know the the taxi driver,  the Judge,  the radio star from WKRP.  Have a laugh,sometimes shed a tear.  Not  all the blood and guts, the people moving from show to show to show and you don't really notice because they all all the same.  For a great half hour stop in and say hi to Alex, Louie, Elaine,Lauca.and enjoy 30 minutes of great  T.V.

reviewText: This is one of my favorite television series of all time.  The writing, acting, and directing went very well together, and probably is the very definition of overachievement.  I haven't seen "Taxi" in a while, and found myself laughing out loud again.  Also, I found a new appreciation for Danny DeVito's acting.  Judd Hirsch won at least one emmy for his role as Alex.  The Louie DePalma character was so over the top, it was easy to take Mr. DeVito's performance for granted.  The casting changes from season to season were unfamiliar, and due to what I am sure are copyright issues, one of the episode with a specific song was butchered.  Toward the end of the series, it didn't have much occupational humor and was more about the estabilished characters.
summary: One of my favorite series of all time.
